# Firebase Patterns & Best Practices

## Firebase Configuration

Firebase is configured in [config/firebase.ts](mdc:src/config/firebase.ts). Always import from this file:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
import { auth, db, googleProvider, appleProvider } from '@/config/firebase';

// ❌ BAD
import { auth } from 'firebase/auth'; // Don't import directly
```

## Collection Names

**Always use constants** from [constants/firebaseCollections.ts](mdc:src/constants/firebaseCollections.ts):

```typescript
import { COLLECTIONS } from '@/constants/firebaseCollections';

// ✅ GOOD
const q = query(
  collection(db, COLLECTIONS.TEACHER_APPLICATIONS),
  where('status', '==', 'approved')
);

// ❌ BAD - Never hardcode collection names
const q = query(
  collection(db, 'teacherApplications'), // Hardcoded string
  where('status', '==', 'approved')
);
```

## Repository Pattern (Required)

**All Firebase operations MUST go through repositories**, never directly in components.

### Repository Location
- Repositories: `infrastructure/firebase/repositories/`
- Example: [TeacherRepository](mdc:src/infrastructure/firebase/repositories/TeacherRepository.ts)

### Repository Structure
```typescript
export class TeacherRepository {
  async findApplicationByUserId(userId: string): Promise<TeacherApplication | null> {
    const q = query(
      collection(db, COLLECTIONS.TEACHER_APPLICATIONS),
      where('userId', '==', userId)
    );
    const snapshot = await getDocs(q);
    // ... transform and return
  }
}
```

### Using Repositories
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Component uses service, service uses repository
const teacherService = new TeacherService();
const profile = await teacherService.getTeacherProfileData(userId);

// ❌ BAD: Component directly queries Firebase
const q = query(collection(db, 'users'), where('id', '==', userId));
const snapshot = await getDocs(q);
```

## Service Layer Pattern

Services orchestrate repositories and apply business logic:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Service coordinates repositories
export class TeacherService {
  private repository: TeacherRepository;
  
  constructor() {
    this.repository = new TeacherRepository();
  }
  
  async getTeacherProfileData(userId: string): Promise<TeacherProfileData> {
    const [application, profile, rating] = await Promise.all([
      this.repository.findApplicationByUserId(userId),
      this.repository.getUserProfile(userId),
      this.repository.getTeacherRating(userId),
    ]);
    // Apply business logic, transform data
    return { application, profile, rating };
  }
}
```

## Data Fetching Patterns

### In Components (via Hooks)
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Use custom hooks
export function useTeacherProfile(userId: string) {
  const [profile, setProfile] = useState<TeacherProfile | null>(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  
  useEffect(() => {
    const teacherService = new TeacherService();
    teacherService.getTeacherProfileData(userId)
      .then(setProfile)
      .finally(() => setLoading(false));
  }, [userId]);
  
  return { profile, loading };
}
```

### Real-time Subscriptions
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Use onSnapshot in repositories
export class TeacherRepository {
  subscribeToProfile(userId: string, callback: (profile: TeacherProfile) => void) {
    const docRef = doc(db, COLLECTIONS.USERS, userId);
    return onSnapshot(docRef, (snapshot) => {
      if (snapshot.exists()) {
        callback(snapshot.data() as TeacherProfile);
      }
    });
  }
}
```

## Error Handling

### Repository Error Handling
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Repositories handle Firebase errors
async findApplicationByUserId(userId: string): Promise<TeacherApplication | null> {
  try {
    const q = query(
      collection(db, COLLECTIONS.TEACHER_APPLICATIONS),
      where('userId', '==', userId)
    );
    const snapshot = await getDocs(q);
    // ... transform
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error finding teacher application:', error);
    throw error; // Re-throw for service layer to handle
  }
}
```

### Service Error Handling
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Services handle business logic errors
async getTeacherProfileData(userId: string): Promise<TeacherProfileData> {
  try {
    // ... repository calls
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error getting teacher profile data:', error);
    throw error; // Or return default/fallback data
  }
}
```

## Query Patterns

### Simple Queries
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Use repository methods
const application = await repository.findApplicationByUserId(userId);
```

### Complex Queries
```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Complex queries in repository
async findApprovedTeachersWithRating(minRating: number) {
  const applications = await this.findAllApproved();
  const teachersWithRatings = await Promise.all(
    applications.map(async (app) => {
      const { rating } = await this.getTeacherRating(app.userId);
      return { ...app, rating };
    })
  );
  return teachersWithRatings.filter(t => t.rating >= minRating);
}
```

## Data Transformation

Transform Firebase data in repositories or services, not in components:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Transform in repository
async getUserProfile(userId: string): Promise<UserProfile | null> {
  const docRef = doc(db, COLLECTIONS.USERS, userId);
  const snapshot = await getDoc(docRef);
  
  if (!snapshot.exists()) return null;
  
  const data = snapshot.data();
  return {
    id: snapshot.id,
    ...data,
    createdAt: data.createdAt?.toDate(),
    updatedAt: data.updatedAt?.toDate(),
  } as UserProfile;
}

// ❌ BAD: Transform in component
useEffect(() => {
  getDoc(docRef).then(snapshot => {
    const data = snapshot.data();
    // Don't transform here
    setProfile(data);
  });
}, []);
```

## Status Constants

Use status constants from [constants/status.ts](mdc:src/constants/status.ts):

```typescript
import { TEACHER_APPLICATION_STATUS } from '@/constants/status';

// ✅ GOOD
where('status', '==', TEACHER_APPLICATION_STATUS.APPROVED)

// ❌ BAD
where('status', '==', 'approved') // Hardcoded string
```

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

1. ❌ **Direct Firebase imports in components** - Use repositories
2. ❌ **Hardcoded collection names** - Use COLLECTIONS constants
3. ❌ **Hardcoded status values** - Use status constants
4. ❌ **Data transformation in components** - Do it in repositories/services
5. ❌ **Multiple queries for same data** - Cache or use single query
6. ❌ **Not handling errors** - Always wrap in try-catch
7. ❌ **Not cleaning up subscriptions** - Return unsubscribe functions

## Best Practices Summary

1. ✅ Always use repositories for Firebase operations
2. ✅ Use services for business logic orchestration
3. ✅ Use constants for collection names and status values
4. ✅ Transform data in repositories/services, not components
5. ✅ Handle errors properly at each layer
6. ✅ Use custom hooks for data fetching in components
7. ✅ Clean up subscriptions in useEffect cleanup
